<title type="html"><![CDATA[CHR-RAM or CHR-ROM? That is the question]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1251&amp;p=11085#p11085"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">Dwedit wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">With CHR-RAM, I heard it's possible to update up to 16 tiles per frame using some tricks used by Battletoads.<br /></div><br />Well, possible it is. You would need to copy 256 bytes in order to draw 16 tiles. The problem is that this is not the only thing you'll be doing in Vblank. You still have to update the name tables and attribute tables as the player moves, write palettes, do sprite OAM... Many other things need VBlank time, so you can't give it all to updating tiles. You could shut the screen off early, or turn it on late, to get more time, but then it gets pretty tricky...</div><br />Not too tricky if you just turn the screen off early. <a href="http://pineight.com/nes/" class="postlink">Tetramino (homebrew)</a> does this for nametable updates. If you're considering developing a PAL-only game and accepting the PAL NES's inherent letterbox, then you could probably get away with turning off the screen way early and turning it on way late in the NTSC version.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Mar 22, 2006 5:33 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
