<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2006-03-21T09:03:28-07:00</updated>
<published>2006-03-21T09:03:28-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1251&amp;p=11041#p11041</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1251&amp;p=11041#p11041"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[CHR-RAM or CHR-ROM? That is the question]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1251&amp;p=11041#p11041"><![CDATA[
CHR-ROM:<br />GOOD:<br />-easier to use (graphics are already there on power up);<br />-fast and easy background animations through bankswitching;<br />BAD:<br />-size of switchable chunks limited by the mapper;<br />-you must have everything you'll need pre-drawn;<br /><br />CHR-RAM:<br />GOOD:<br />-dynamic effects calculated at run-time;<br />-you can manipulate any tile however you want;<br />-you can compress the graphics (not really an advantage...);<br />BAD:<br />-although you can change them as you want, it's a slow process, wich makes changing many tiles at a time when inside a game impossible;<br /><br />Also, if you are going to put the game on a cart you must work with what you have. If you have a CHR-RAM cart, it is easier to just swap the PRG with your own. But CHR-RAM carts are not that common, are they?<br /><br />Well, if it's just a simple demo using only one tileset, I'd say go with CHR-ROM. The CHR file can just be appended to the PRG and you ready to use the graphics, you don't even need to code a routine that will upload the graphics, they'll just be hardcoded there.<br /><br />I tend to like CHR-ROM better, but I can admit that CHR-RAM has it's advantages. And it seems to be common that CHR-RAM is used in the Dev scene, maybe because it's easier to reprogram only 1 chip (PRG) instead of 2.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Tue Mar 21, 2006 9:03 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
